# containerd APT Repository

[containerd](https://containerd.io) is an industry-standard container runtime with an emphasis on
simplicity, robustness, and portability. It manages the complete container lifecycle of its host
system: image transfer and storage, container execution and supervision, low-level storage and
network attachments, and more. containerd is a graduated CNCF project and the runtime used
underneath Docker, Kubernetes (via CRI), and many other container platforms.

This repository provides **unofficial** Debian/Ubuntu `.deb` packages for containerd,
built automatically from official upstream releases and published as an APT repository
at [pkgs.bil.co.ua](https://pkgs.bil.co.ua) via Cloudflare R2.

---

## Compatibility

This package uses the official pre-built upstream binaries from
[containerd/containerd releases](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/releases).
The binaries are statically compiled Go executables with no distribution-specific
dependencies, and work on any reasonably modern Debian or Ubuntu release
(`amd64` and `arm64`).

---

## Packages

| Package              | Description                                                         |
|----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `containerd`         | The containerd daemon and runtime shim(s)                           |
| `containerd-tools`   | Client tools: `ctr`, `containerd-stress`                           |

---

## Installation

### 1. Add the GPG signing key

```sh
sudo mkdir -p /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL {{PAGES_URL}}/public.asc | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/containerd.gpg
```

### 2. Add the repository

```sh
echo "deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/containerd.gpg] {{PAGES_URL}} containerd main" \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/containerd.list
```

### 3. Pin the repository

```sh
echo -e 'Package: *\nPin: release a=containerd\nPin-Priority: 1001' \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/preferences.d/containerd
```

### 4. Update and install

```sh
sudo apt update
```

Install the runtime:

```sh
sudo apt install containerd
```

Install the runtime and client tools:

```sh
sudo apt install containerd containerd-tools
```

---

## Configuration

A default configuration file is generated at `/etc/containerd/config.toml`
during installation. To regenerate it:

```sh
sudo containerd config default | sudo tee /etc/containerd/config.toml
sudo systemctl restart containerd
```

> **Kubernetes users:** you will likely want to set the cgroup driver to `systemd`:
> ```sh
> sudo sed -i 's/SystemdCgroup = false/SystemdCgroup = true/' /etc/containerd/config.toml
> sudo systemctl restart containerd
> ```

---

## Starting the service

The service is installed but **not enabled** by default.

```sh
# Enable and start now
sudo systemctl enable --now containerd

# Or start without enabling at boot
sudo systemctl start containerd
```

---

## Package details

### `containerd`

- Installs the `containerd` binary to `/usr/bin/`
- Installs the `containerd-shim-runc-v2` shim to `/usr/bin/`
- Default state directory: `/var/lib/containerd/`
- Configuration file: `/etc/containerd/config.toml` (generated on first install)
- Unix socket: `/run/containerd/containerd.sock`
- systemd unit: `containerd.service` (installed but **not enabled** by default)
- Runs as **root** — required for namespace and cgroup management

### `containerd-tools`

- `ctr` — low-level containerd CLI for direct interaction with the daemon
- `containerd-stress` — stress-testing utility for the containerd daemon

> **Note:** `ctr` is a low-level debugging and administrative tool.
> For day-to-day use, prefer higher-level tools such as `nerdctl` or `crictl`.

---

## Notes on `runc`

containerd delegates container process creation to [runc](https://github.com/opencontainers/runc)
via `containerd-shim-runc-v2`. The `runc` binary must be installed separately:

```sh
sudo apt install runc
```

---

## Build details

- Packages use the official pre-built upstream binaries from [containerd/containerd releases](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/releases)
- Packages are GPG-signed
